<ul><li>The object-oriented methodology forces designers to go through an <b>extensive planning phase</b>, which makes for better design and fewer weaknesses.</li><li>Once an object is created, knowledge of how its methods are implemented is not necessary in order for a programmer to use it.</li><li><b>New objects</b> can easily be created with small differences to existing ones.</li><li><b>Re-usability</b>&nbsp;- objects that are defined, coded and tested and be used in many programs.<br></li></ul>